I think most of these are actually not correct.
@RequiresAPI means it's up to the caller to only call the method/class if they're on that API level or higher.
@TargetAPI means that the method/class is certifying that it's safe for it to be used on any API level, as long as the internal methods use APIs less than or equal to the specified target API.
In most of these cases the methods themselves are checking the SDK version, so we should be using @TargetApi.

@TargetApi is basically @SuppressWarnings for API checks, except that it's limited to a maximum sdk version so that it doesn't silently suppress warnings for a newer API level if you modify the method later on to use a new sdk level that you're not checking against.
For example if we use a method that requires android O, check it properly with an if/else, suppress the warning with @SuppressWarnings, and then go back and add a method that requires O MR1, we won't see a lint or ide warning about the unsafe O MR1 call. TargetApi fixes that by warning for all methods past whatever level you give it.
So using @TargetApi makes sense whenever @SuppressWarnings would make sense, it's just a bit safer.

